  "prompt": "How do I capture raw images from an Android camera?",
  "response": "Capturing raw images on an Android device allows you to obtain unprocessed sensor data, which provides greater flexibility for post-processing (such as adjusting exposure, white balance, and more) without degrading image quality. To capture raw images programmatically, you can use the Android `Camera2` API, which offers comprehensive control over camera functions. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you achieve this:\n\n### 1. **Prerequisites**\n\n- **Device Compatibility:** Ensure that the Android device supports RAW capture. Not all devices are capable of capturing RAW images. You can check this by querying the camera's capabilities.\n  \n- **Permissions:** Your app needs to request camera permissions (`CAMERA`) and, if saving files, storage permissions (`WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE` or use scoped storage appropriately).\n\n- **Development Environment:** Knowledge of Android development in Java or Kotlin and familiarity with Android Studio.\n\n### 2. **Check for RAW Support**\n\nBefore attempting to capture RAW images, verify that the device's camera supports the RAW format (`RAW_SENSOR`):\n\n```java\nCameraManager cameraManager = (CameraManager) context.getSystemService(Context.CAMERA_SERVICE);\ntry {\n    for (String cameraId : cameraManager.getCameraIdList()) {\n        CameraCharacteristics characteristics = cameraManager.getCameraCharacteristics(cameraId);\n        int[] capabilities = characteristics.get(CameraCharacteristics.REQUEST_AVAILABLE_CAPABILITIES);\n        boolean isRawSupported = false;\n        for (int cap : capabilities) {\n            if (cap == CameraCharacteristics.REQUEST_AVAILABLE_CAPABILITIES_RAW) {\n                isRawSupported = true;\n                break;\n            }\n        }\n        if (isRawSupported) {\n            // This camera supports RAW capture\n        }\n    }\n} catch (CameraAccessException e) {\n    e.printStackTrace();\n}\n```\n\n### 3. **Set Up Camera2 API for RAW Capture**\n\nHere's a high-level overview of the steps involved:\n\n1. **Initialize CameraManager and Select Camera:**\n   Choose the appropriate camera (usually rear-facing) that supports RAW.\n\n2. **Set Up a `CameraDevice.StateCallback`:**\n   Handle camera device state changes such as `onOpened`, `onDisconnected`, and `onError`.\n\n3. **Create a `CaptureRequest` for RAW Capture:**\n   Configure the request to include a RAW image capture.\n\n4. **Set Up an `ImageReader` for RAW Images:**\n   Use `ImageFormat.RAW_SENSOR` or `ImageFormat.DNG` depending on your requirements.\n\n5. **Handle Image Saving:**\n   Convert the RAW data to a desired format (commonly DNG) and save it to storage.\n\n### 4. **Sample Code Snippet**\n\nBelow is a simplified example in Kotlin to illustrate the process:\n\n```kotlin\nimport android.Manifest\nimport android.content.Context\nimport android.content.pm.PackageManager\nimport android.graphics.ImageFormat\nimport android.hardware.camera2.*\nimport android.media.Image\nimport android.media.ImageReader\nimport android.os.Environment\nimport androidx.core.app.ActivityCompat\nimport java.io.File\nimport java.io.FileOutputStream\nimport java.nio.ByteBuffer\n\nfun captureRawImage(context: Context) {\n    val cameraManager = context.getSystemService(Context.CAMERA_SERVICE) as CameraManager\n    try {\n        val cameraId = cameraManager.cameraIdList.first { id ->\n            val characteristics = cameraManager.getCameraCharacteristics(id)\n            val caps = characteristics.get(CameraCharacteristics.REQUEST_AVAILABLE_CAPABILITIES)\n            caps?.contains(CameraCharacteristics.REQUEST_AVAILABLE_CAPABILITIES_RAW) == true\n        }\n\n        val characteristics = cameraManager.getCameraCharacteristics(cameraId)\n        val sensorSize = characteristics.get(CameraCharacteristics.SENSOR_INFO_PIXEL_ARRAY_SIZE)\n\n        val imageReader = ImageReader.newInstance(\n            sensorSize.width, sensorSize.height,\n            ImageFormat.RAW_SENSOR,\n            /* maxImages= */ 2\n        )\n\n        if (ActivityCompat.checkSelfPermission(context, Manifest.permission.CAMERA) != PackageManager.PERMISSION_GRANTED) {\n            // Handle permission request\n            return\n        }\n\n        cameraManager.openCamera(cameraId, object : CameraDevice.StateCallback() {\n            override fun onOpened(camera: CameraDevice) {\n                val captureRequestBuilder = camera.createCaptureRequest(CameraDevice.TEMPLATE_STILL_CAPTURE)\n                captureRequestBuilder.addTarget(imageReader.surface)\n                // Optionally, enable RAW capture\n                captureRequestBuilder.set(CaptureRequest.CONTROL_ENABLE_RAW, true)\n\n                // Create a session\n                camera.createCaptureSession(\n                    listOf(imageReader.surface),\n                    object : CameraCaptureSession.StateCallback() {\n                        override fun onConfigured(session: CameraCaptureSession) {\n                            session.capture(captureRequestBuilder.build(), object : CameraCaptureSession.CaptureCallback() {\n                                override fun onCaptureCompleted(\n                                    session: CameraCaptureSession,\n                                    request: CaptureRequest,\n                                    result: TotalCaptureResult\n                                ) {\n                                    // Capture completed\n                                }\n                            }, null)\n                        }\n\n                        override fun onConfigureFailed(session: CameraCaptureSession) {\n                            // Handle configuration failure\n                        }\n                    },\n                    null\n                )\n            }\n\n            override fun onDisconnected(camera: CameraDevice) {\n                camera.close()\n            }\n\n            override fun onError(camera: CameraDevice, error: Int) {\n                camera.close()\n            }\n        }, null)\n\n        imageReader.setOnImageAvailableListener({ reader ->\n            val image: Image = reader.acquireLatestImage()\n            // Process and save the RAW image\n            saveRawImage(image)\n            image.close()\n        }, null)\n\n    } catch (e: CameraAccessException) {\n        e.printStackTrace()\n    }\n}\n\nfun saveRawImage(image: Image) {\n    val buffer: ByteBuffer = image.planes[0].buffer\n    val bytes = ByteArray(buffer.capacity())\n    buffer.get(bytes)\n    \n    // Typically, RAW images are saved in DNG format. You might need to use a library to convert RAW_SENSOR data to DNG.\n    // For simplicity, saving raw bytes directly (not recommended for actual RAW processing)\n    val file = File(Environment.getExternalStorageDirectory(), \"raw_image.raw\")\n    try {\n        FileOutputStream(file).use { output ->\n            output.write(bytes)\n        }\n    } catch (e: Exception) {\n        e.printStackTrace()\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Notes:**\n\n- **DNG Conversion:** RAW_SENSOR data from Android's Camera2 API is typically not in the standard DNG format. To create a proper DNG file, you may need to use additional libraries or implement the DNG specification, which can be complex. Libraries like [dcraw](https://www.cybercom.net/~dcoffin/dcraw/) (though primarily for desktops) or other specialized Android libraries might be required.\n\n- **Threading:** The `ImageReader` callbacks run on the thread you specify. Make sure to handle threading appropriately to avoid blocking the UI.\n\n- **Error Handling:** The sample code omits robust error handling for brevity. In production code, ensure you handle all possible exceptions and edge cases.\n\n### 5. **Using Existing Libraries and Tools**\n\nIf implementing RAW capture from scratch is too involved, consider using existing libraries or apps that facilitate RAW image capture:\n\n- **CameraX Extension:** Google\u2019s CameraX library is a higher-level abstraction over Camera2 and may simplify some tasks, though RAW support is primarily via Camera2.\n\n- **Open Camera:** An open-source camera app that supports RAW capture on compatible devices. You can study its source code for reference: [Open Camera GitHub](https://github.com/almalence/OpenCamera).\n\n### 6. **Alternative: Using Third-Party Camera Apps**\n\nIf your goal is to capture RAW images without developing an app, numerous third-party camera applications support RAW capture:\n\n- **Open Camera:** Free and open-source, supports RAW capture (DNG) on devices that support it.\n  \n- **Adobe Lightroom Mobile:** Offers RAW capture and powerful editing tools.\n\n- **ProCam, Camera FV-5:** Paid apps that provide RAW capture and advanced camera controls.\n\n### 7. **Post-Processing RAW Images**\n\nAfter capturing RAW images, you can process them using image editing software that supports RAW formats, such as:\n\n- **Adobe Lightroom or Photoshop**\n\n- **Darktable or RawTherapee (open-source)**\n\n- **Mobile Apps:** Snapseed, Adobe Lightroom Mobile\n\n### 8. **Additional Considerations**\n\n- **Device Variability:** Different Android devices may have varying levels of support and behavior for RAW capture. Always test on target devices.\n\n- **Performance:** RAW image processing can be resource-intensive. Optimize your app for performance, especially when handling large images.\n\n- **User Experience:** Provide clear information to users about RAW image capture, as RAW files are significantly larger than JPEGs and may require more storage space.\n\n### 9. **References and Further Reading**\n\n- **Android Camera2 API Documentation:** [Camera2 API Guide](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/hardware/camera2/package-summary)\n  \n- **Sample Code from Google:** [Camera2Raw](https://github.com/android/camera-samples/tree/main/Camera2Raw)\n  \n- **DNG Specification:** [Adobe DNG Specification](https://www.adobe.com/content/dam/acom/en/products/photoshop/pdfs/DNG_Spec_1.6.pdf)\n\nBy following these guidelines and utilizing the appropriate APIs and tools, you can successfully capture and handle raw images on Android devices, enabling high-quality photography within your applications.",
